value.value: Temporary muscle that lies underneath the adult dorsal head (vertex) and extends transversely between the compound eyes. The contraction of this muscle layer diminishes the volume of the head. As with other temporary eclosion muscles, it soon degenerates and is not found in older flies.

Temporary muscle that is inserted on the ptilinum at each side dorso-laterally as a narrow band, immediately in front of the line of demarcation between the vertex and the ptilinum. As with other temporary eclosion muscles, it degenerates 20h after adult emergence.

Unpaired, long and thin muscle that arises from the dorsal rim of the occipital foramen and connects to the lunule of the fronto-clypeus. It retracts the ptilinum and the fronto-clypeus after adult emergence.

Muscle inserted on the adult ocular sclerites at the dorso-cephalic margin of the compound eyes, connecting to the second antennal segment. It functions to deflate the head during emergence by approximating the vertex and the fronto-clypeus and to retract the antenna. By 72h after emergence, the muscles have completely disintegrated.

Somatic muscle that contributes to movement of the head, via the neck (Gorko et al., 2024). Most neck muscle cells are contained in the thorax and control head movements either through long tendons that travel through the neck to attach to the head directly or indirectly by moving the cervical sclerite (Gorko et al., 2024). Most neck muscles are innervated by a single motor neuron (Gorko et al., 2024).
Muscle of the adult neck, located dorsally.
Short dorsal cervical muscle that has a dorsomedial attachment to an apodeme and extends in a ventral anterior lateral direction to the vicinity of the anterior end of muscle 23 (Miller, 1950).

Dorsal cervical muscle that connects to the cervical sclerite and extends anterodorsally to the pronotum (Miller, 1950; Strausfeld et al., 1987; Gorko et al., 2024). It is innervated by the DProN4 motor neuron (Gorko et al., 2024).

definition.value: Based on straight anteroposterior orientation, this seems to correspond to the LEV muscle in Gorko et al. (2024).

value.value: Dorsal cervical muscle that connects to the cervical sclerite and extends dorsomedially to the pronotum (Miller, 1950; Strausfeld et al., 1987; Gorko et al., 2024). It is innervated by the DProN5 motor neuron (Gorko et al., 2024).

definition.value: Based on dorsoventral orientation, attachment of ventral end to the cervical sclerite and mapping of muscle 21 to LEV, this seems to correspond to the AD muscle in Gorko et al. (2024).

value.value: Relatively long dorsal neck muscle, extending further posteriorly than other dorsal neck muscles (Miller, 1950; Lawrence, 1982).
Lateral cervical muscle that connects to a cervical sclerite anteriorly, extending then laterally and posteriorly, and inserting in the same region as dorsal cervical muscle 21.

Muscle of the adult neck that attaches to the prothoracic sternal apodeme and extends anteriorly (Miller, 1950; Rivlin et al., 2004). It occupies a relatively ventral position (Miller, 1950; Rivlin et al., 2004). There are three of these on each side (Miller, 1950; Rivlin et al., 2004).

Ventral cervical muscle that connects to a more posterior medial region of the sternal apodeme than muscle 26 (Miller, 1950; Rivlin et al., 2004). There is one of these muscles on each side, innervated by a single motor neuron (Koenig and Ikeda, 1989; Gorko et al., 2024). Its motor neuron arrives via the cervical nerve and forms a branch for each of the six muscle fibers, with each branch bifurcating to run anterior-posterior along its fiber (Koenig and Ikeda, 1989).

definition.value: Based on sternal apodeme attachment posteromedial to muscle 26 and innervation via cervical nerve, this seems to correspond to SC-RE in Gorko et al. (2024).

value.value: Ventral cervical muscle that connects to a more anterior lateral region of the sternal apodeme than muscle 25 (Miller, 1950; Rivlin et al., 2004). It is spindle-shaped and comprises 3-4 fibers (Rivlin et al., 2004).

definition.value: Based on sternal apodeme attachment between muscles 25 and 27, this seems to correspond to SC-RO in Gorko et al. (2024). Two of these exist per side in Calliphora (Strausfeld et al., 1987 - doi:10.1007/BF00609727).

value.value: Ventral cervical muscle that connects to a relatively anterior lateral region of the sternal apophysis (Miller, 1950; Rivlin et al., 2004). It extends through the neck to the posterior head (Miller, 1950).
Somatic muscle that is part of the adult thorax.
Thoracic muscle that has its insertion site more anterior, as compared to thoracic remotor muscles.
Promotor muscle that arises from the tergum.
Promotor muscle of the adult thorax that attaches to the inner surface of the sternum.
Promotor muscle of the adult thorax that attaches to the inner surface of the pleura.
Thoracic muscle that has its insertion site more posterior, as compared to thoracic promotor muscles.
Remotor muscle of the adult thorax that attaches to the inner surface of the sternum.
Remotor muscle of the adult thorax that attaches to the inner surface of the pleura.
Muscle capable of rotating a body part.
Rotator muscle found in the anterior region of the coxal base.
Rotator muscle found in the posterior region of the coxal base.
Muscle that draws some body part back to position.
Leg muscle that is found within the leg.
Muscle that lowers some part of the leg.
Depressor muscle connecting the coxa and the thoracic exoskeleton. It extends the coxa-trochanter joint (Azevedo et al., 2024).
Depressor muscle of the adult leg that extends along the medial coxa and attaches to the distal coxa. It is composed of 8 to 10 fibers (Soler et al., 2004).
Muscle that extends along the femur and attaches to the proximal tibia. It is composed of 26 fibers (Kuan et al., 2020). It flexes the femur-tibia joint (Azevedo et al., 2024).

Adult leg muscle that extends along the tibia and attaches to the proximal tarsus, via the tarsal depressor tendon (Soler et al., 2004). It is composed of 20 to 33 fibers, with a markedly lower number of cells in the prothoracic leg than in the mesothoracic and metathoracic legs (Soler et al., 2004). It extends the tibia-tarsus joint, which raises the fly's body when standing (Azevedo et al., 2024).
Adult leg muscle attached via the long tendon to the unguitractor plate of the pretarsus. There are two of these muscles, one located in the femur and one in the tibia (Soler et al., 2004).
Muscle that raises some part of the leg.
Levator muscle of the adult coxa that extends along the coxa and attaches to the distal coxa.
Levator muscle of the adult coxa that extends along the lateral coxa and attaches to the distal coxa.
Levator muscle of the adult coxa that extends along the medial coxa and attaches to the distal coxa.
Muscle that extends along the femur and attaches to the proximal tibia. It is composed of 36 fibers (Kuan et al., 2020). It extends the femur-tibia joint (Azevedo et al., 2024).

Adult leg muscle located dorsally within the distal tibia, attaching to the proximal tarsus via the tarsal levator tendon (Soler et al., 2004). It flexes the tibia-tarsus joint, which lowers the fly's body when standing (Azevedo et al., 2024). It is composed of 8 to 10 fibers (Soler et al., 2004).
A small muscle located at the distal end of a leg segment and producing a slight backward movement (reduction) of the next segment (Chapman, 1998).
Reductor muscle of the adult leg that originates at the base of the trochanter and attaches to the proximal femur. It is composed of 4 or 5 fibers (Soler et al., 2004).
Somatic muscle that is part of the prothorax.
Promotor muscle of the prothoracic segment.
Large muscle of the adult prothorax that arises dorsally on the tergum and extends ventrally to the anterior coxa (Snodgrass, 1935; Miller, 1950). It moves the coxa anteriorly (Azevedo et al., 2024).

label.value: prothoracic pleural remotor and abductor muscle 29

value.value: Adult muscle of the prothorax that arises dorsally and extends ventrally to attach to the coxa (Miller, 1950). It moves the coxa posteriorly and laterally (Azevedo et al., 2024).
Adult prothoracic muscle that arises on the episternum and extends posteriorly to insert on the anterior coxa (Snodgrass, 1935; Miller, 1950). It moves the coxa anteriorly (Azevedo et al., 2024).
Sternal muscle of the anterior adult prothorax.

Large adult prothoracic muscle that originates on the medial plate of the sternal apophysis (sternal furca) at the midline and extends laterally, attaching to the anterior part of the coxa (Rivlin et al., 2004). It is composed of 6-7 fibers (Rivlin et al., 2004). It moves the coxa anteriorly (Azevedo et al., 2024).
Adult prothoracic muscle that originates on the sternum and inserts on the anterior part of the coxal base (Snodgrass, 1935; Miller, 1950). It moves the coxa posteriorly (Azevedo et al., 2024).
